Thermodynamics
We model the helix as a double-stranded (ds) B-DNA helical structure and the coil as a single-stranded (ss) helical structure (see the ‘‘Structural models for dsDNA and ssDNA’’ section in Appendix A). The folding free energy (helix stability) DGT° for the helix-coil transition is calculated as the difference between the helix and the coil:
DGT° 1⁄4 GT°ðhelixÞ ÿ GT°ðcoilÞ: (1)
Here T is the temperature, GT°(helix) and GT°(coil) are the free energies for the helix and the coil, respectively. DGT° is dependent on the temperature, the structures of the ds helix and the ss helix, and the solvent conditions, such as the salt concentration and the cation properties. As an approximation, we decompose DGT° into two parts: a nonelectrostatic contribution DGnel
T and an electrostatic contribution DGel
T (32,33,56–60):
DGT° 1⁄4 DGnel
