examples of the tightly bound regions around a ssDNA and a dsDNA helix in a Mg21 solution. For a N-bp double-stranded nucleic acid molecule, there are 2N phosphates. We divide the whole tightly bound region into 2N cells, each around a phosphate. In a cell, say, the i-th cell, there can exist mi 1⁄4 0, 1, 2. . . tightly bound ions. Each possible set of the 2N numbers {m1, m2, . . . , m2N} defines a binding mode. There exist a large number of such binding modes. For example, if we allow at most two ions in each cell, there would be 32N modes for the tightly bound ions. The total partition function Z is given by the sum over all the possible binding modes M:
Z1⁄4+
