37 1⁄4 Gel
37ðhelixÞ ÿ Gel
37ðcoilÞ (see Eq. 1), i.e., higher salt concentration tends to stabilize the helix. From Fig. 2 a, we find that PB and TBI give nearly the same results for the NaCl solution. This is because the interion correlations are negligible for the NaCl solution considered here (55). However, for MgCl2 solution, as shown in Fig. 2 b, we find that the TBI model gives lower free energy than the PB. This is because the low-energy correlated states of the bound Mg21 ions, which are explicitly considered in TBI, are neglected in the PB. The average mean-field states
considered in PB have higher energies than the low-energy correlated states, causing the PB to underestimate the helix stability in the MgCl2 solution.
Folding free energy DG3°7
Combining the electrostatic free energy Gel
37 and the chemical
free energy Gnel
37 ; we obtain the total free energy DG3°7(1⁄4 the ds helix stability). We investigate the dependence of the helix stability as a function of the NaCl and the MgCl2 concentrations for different DNA sequences and different helix lengths. Fig. 2, c and d, show our computed results as well as the experimental results. As we expected, both Fig. 2, c and d, show that higher ion concentration supports higher helix stability (lower DG3°7).
