In the MgCl2 solution
Fig. 5 b shows the melting temperatures Tm of dsDNA helix in the MgCl2 solution as a function of the ion concentration for two sequences. In contrast to the folding free energy DG37° in Fig. 2 d, which has very limited experimental data, more experimental data for Tm in pure MgCl2 solutions are available. We find that the Tm’s predicted from the TBI model agree with the available experimental data over a wide MgCl2 concentration range from 0.3 mM to 0.3 M. Again we
find that PB theory can predict the trend in the [Mg21]dependence of Tm but it underestimates the helix stability and the Tm due to the neglected correlation and fluctuation effects, as discussed in the previous sections.
